<CourseModuleIntroduction Module="@CourseBook.CSharpCourse["reflection"]">
    <MudText GutterBottom="true">
        The ability to self-reflect is very important, not only for humans.
        Reflection in .NET allows many metadata driven solutions that we otherwise
        take for granted. All testing frameworks, ASP.NET, Entity Framework, JSON serializers,
        and who knows what else depend on reflection.
    </MudText>
    <MudText GutterBottom="true">
        Reflection used correctly is relatively fast and very powerful. Used incorrectly
        it becomes an ugly hack. Reflection performance is much lower than regular code,
        sometimes orders of magnitude slower. This is by design &ndash; the design goals
        of the CLR explicitly state that reflection being fast in all cases is <em>not</em>
        a goal.
    </MudText>
